05976nam a22007575i 9780292794337DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927943377 a10.7560/7141752doi  a(DE-B1597)586689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1435.3.W55bS64 2006eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.800972/7522200aDissident Women :bGender and Cultural Politics in Chiapas /ced. by Shannon Speed, Lynn M. Stephen, R. Aída Hernández Castillo. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACRONYMS AND ABBREVIATIONS -- tPreface: Indigenous Organizing and the Ezln in the Context of Neoliberalism in Mexico -- tAcknowledgments -- tSection One: Key Women’s Documents -- tWomen’s Revolutionary Law -- tWomen’s Rights in Our Traditions and Customs -- tComandanta Esther: Speech before the Mexican Congress -- tInternational Day of the Rebel Woman -- tIntroduction -- tSection Two: Indigenous women’s organizing in Chiapas and Mexico: historical trajectories, border crossings -- tChapter 1. Between Feminist Ethnocentricity and Ethnic Essentialism: The Zapatistas’ Demands and the National Indigenous Women’s Movement -- tChapter 2. Indigenous Women and Zapatismo: New Horizons of Visibility -- tChapter 3. Gender and Stereotypes in the Social Movements of Chiapas -- tChapter 4. Weaving in the Spaces: Indigenous Women’s Organizing and the Politics of Scale in Mexico -- tSection Three: Rights and gender in ethnographic context -- tChapter 5. Indigenous Women’s Activism in Oaxaca and Chiapas -- tChapter 6. Autonomy and a Handful of Herbs: Contesting Gender and Ethnic Identities through Healing -- tChapter 7. Rights at the Intersection: Gender and Ethnicity in Neoliberal Mexico -- tChapter 8. “We Can No Longer Be Like Hens with Our Heads Bowed, We Must Raise Our Heads and Look Ahead”: A Consideration of the Daily Life of Zapatista Women -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYielding pivotal new perspectives on the indigenous women of Mexico, Dissident Women: Gender and Cultural Politics in Chiapas presents a diverse collection of voices exploring the human rights and gender issues that gained international attention after the first public appearance of the Zapatista National Liberation Army (EZLN) in 1994. Drawing from studies on topics ranging from the daily life of Zapatista women to the effect of transnational indigenous women in tipping geopolitical scales, the contributors explore both the personal and global implications of indigenous women's activism. The Zapatista movement and the Women's Revolutionary Law, a charter that came to have tremendous symbolic importance for thousands of indigenous women, created the potential for renegotiating gender roles in Zapatista communities. Drawing on the original research of scholars with long-term field experience in a range of Mayan communities in Chiapas and featuring several key documents written by indigenous women articulating their vision, Dissident Women brings fresh insight to the revolutionary crossroads at which Chiapas stands—and to the worldwide implications of this economic and political microcosm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMaya womenzMexicozChiapasxPolitics and government. 0aMaya womenzMexicozChiapasxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBlackwell, Maylei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForbis, Melissa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarza Caligaris, Anna María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g